    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1970-05-21T12:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1970-05-21T12:30:00-05:00" n="174"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d174">
                <head>174. Telegram 1246 From the Embassy in Costa Rica to the Department of
                        State<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d174fn1">Source: National Archives,
                        RG 59, Central Files 1970–73, POL 1 COSTA RICA. Confidential. It was
                        repeated to Guatemala City, Managua, San Salvador, Tegucigalpa, and
                            CINCSO/<gloss target="#POLAD1">POLAD</gloss>.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d174fn2">The Embassy reported that President
                            <persName corresp="#p_FFJ1">Figueres</persName> told Ambassador
                            <persName corresp="#p_PWC1">Ploeser</persName> that Costa Rica intended
                        to conduct trade with the communist bloc, but that it would remain firmly on
                        the U.S. side.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>San Jose</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1970-05-21T17:30:00+00:00">May 21, 1970, 1730Z</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <pb facs="d174-1" n="1" xml:id="pg_d174-1"/>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>Subj:</head>
                    <item>Figueres’ Views on Relations With Communist Bloc</item>
                </list>
                <list type="references">
                    <head>Ref:</head>
                    <item>San Jose 1237</item>
                </list>
                <p>1. In May 20 discussion with Amb Ploeser, Figueres said he wants <gloss
                        target="#USG1">USG</gloss> know that he prepared trade with communist bloc
                    when such trade to CR’s advantage but that politically <gloss target="#GOCR1"
                        >GOCR</gloss> will remain firmly on US side.</p>
                <p>2. Figueres said Cuba definitely constitutes exception with respect his open door
                    attitude towards communist bloc. He continues have very strong antipathy towards
                    Castro and considers his detention political prisoners particularly
                    repugnant.</p>
                <p>3. Figueres said wishes make CR showplace of economic/social development which
                    will contrast sharply with situation Cuba. To this end he particularly
                    interested improving port and transportation facilities and making outstanding
                    success his qte war on poverty unqte. Latter connection he expressed active
                    interest progress agricultural sector loan.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PSM1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Pringle</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
